  <h1>TTT — Tri-Tetra Symmetry Model</h1>
  <p>Symmetry · Balance · Emergent Center</p>
</header>

<section>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    TTT is a geometric model based on vector balance and symmetry.
    It describes how stable structures emerge from minimal configurations
    such as the tetrahedron and extend to spherical symmetry.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Core Theorem</h2>
  <code>
    v₁ + v₂ + v₃ + v₄ = 0
  </code>
  <p>
    When four vectors sum to zero, they form a tetrahedral configuration.
    The angle between them is approximately 109.47°.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Geometric Structure</h2>
  <p>
    3 vectors → triangle (plane)<br>
    4 vectors → tetrahedron (3D stability)<br>
    Dual → octahedron<br>
    Limit → spherical symmetry
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Spherical Modes</h2>
  <p>
    The 3-directional structure corresponds to the l = 1 spherical harmonic mode,
    representing the fundamental rotational symmetry in 3D space.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Spectral Structure</h2>
  <code>
    j₁(z) = 0
    z₁ ≈ 4.4934
    z₂ ≈ 7.7252
    z₃ ≈ 10.9041
  </code>
  <p>
    These values define discrete modes in a spherical system.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Hypothesis</h2>
  <p>
    These spectral modes may correspond to hierarchical structures in physics.
    This remains a hypothesis and requires further validation.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Interpretation</h2>
  <p>
    Stability emerges from balance, not dominance.
    The center is not predefined, but arises from symmetry.
  </p>
</section>

